05700nam a22007815i 9783110795295DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107952957 a10.1515/97831107952952doi  a(DE-B1597)625954  a(OCoLC)1378176697  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aAfrican languages from a Role and Reference Grammar perspective :bStudies on the syntax-semantics-pragmatics interface /ced. by Jens Fleischhauer, Claudius Patrick Kihara. 1aDüsseldorf : bdüsseldorf university press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (V, 196 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAfrican languages from a Role and Reference Grammar perspective: An introduction -- tA Functional Typology of Igbo Multi-verb Constructions -- tThe syntax-semantics interface of serial verb constructions in Kwa languages -- tPostverbal Qualifiers and Constraints on Contrastive Focus -- tA Case for the Antipassive in Babungo -- tThe Morphosyntax of the Gĩkũyũ Complex Reference Phrase -- tArgument doubling and right-dislocation - An RRG analysis of head-marking in isiZulu -- tIndex -- tLanguage index0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe volume is a collection of papers which apply Role & Reference Grammar (RRG) to African languages. RRG is a functional theory of syntax which has been developed on the basis of two leading questions: First, how would a syntactic theory look like which starts from 'exotic' languages rather than English? Second, how can the interaction between syntax, semantics and pragmatics in different grammatical systems best modelled and explained? Although RRG took linguistic diversity serious from its very beginning, African languages have been underrepresented in the development of the theory. Given the sheer number African languages deserve a wider coverage in a syntactic theory which takes linguistic diversity seriously. The volume is intended to fill this gap and comprises a selection of papers which investigate different aspects related to the syntax-semantics-pragmatics interface of different African languages. This includes: argument doubling and dislocation in iziZulu, complex referential phrases in Gĩkũyũ, serial verb constructions in Igbo, locative complements in Hausa and Zarma Chiine and focus constructions in Emai. The papers will extent the current RRG approach to new languages and phenomena.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aAfrikanische Sprachen. 4aArgument ‹Linguistik›. 4aGrammatik. 4aInformationsstruktur.  aAfrican languages.  aArgument (linguistics).  aGrammar.  aInformation structure.1 aAnderson, Ciara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgbokhare, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleischhauer, Jens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleischhauer, Jens, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKihara, Claudius Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKihara, Claudius Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRiccio, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaefer, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSennen Agbo, Maduabuchi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is